<header class="header">
  <h1>How to Plan a Garden in a Short Growing Season</h1>

  <p class="tagline">
    Short seasons require climate-based precision.
  </p>

  <p class="lede">
    In a typical year, your growing season is bounded by frost at <strong>32°F (0°C)</strong>.
    But in short-season climates, the true constraint is not just when frost begins and ends —
    it’s how much heat accumulates before frost returns.
  </p>

  <p>
    Short growing seasons expose the weakness of calendar-based advice.
    In long climates, planting errors are often absorbed by excess time and heat.
    In short climates, there is no excess — small mismatches can push crops across the frost boundary before maturity.
  </p>

  <p>
    A seed packet labeled “95 days to maturity” may appear safe in a 100-day season.
    But if daily temperatures are cool and seasonal accumulation is slow, those 95 calendar days may not produce enough heat for maturity.
    In short climates, development is limited by accumulated heat — not by calendar duration alone.
  </p>
</header>

<section class="card">
  <h2>What Counts as a Short Growing Season?</h2>

  <p>
    Frost dates are framed using 1991–2020 climate normals at the <strong>50% probability level</strong>.
    That means your listed frost boundaries represent what typically happens — not a guarantee.
  </p>

  <p>
    A short growing season often means:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>90–120 frost-free days</li>
    <li>Earlier first fall frost</li>
    <li>Cooler early and late season temperatures</li>
    <li>Lower total accumulated Growing Degree Days (GDD)</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    You can determine your local frost window using the
    <a href="/tools/frost-date-finder/">Frost Date Finder</a>.
  </p>

  <p>
    But season length alone does not determine crop success.
    Two gardeners can have similar frost-free day counts and still see very different outcomes because their seasonal heat accumulation differs.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Why Frost-Free Days Aren’t Enough</h2>

  <p>
    Many gardeners focus on “days to maturity.”
    But as explained in
    <a href="/guides/why-days-to-maturity-isnt-enough-in-cold-climates/">Why Days to Maturity Isn’t Enough in Cold Climates</a>,
    development speed depends on temperature — not calendar days alone.
  </p>

  <p>
    Two climates can both have 115 frost-free days.
    One may accumulate 2,400 GDD.
    Another may accumulate 1,700.
  </p>

  <p>
    The calendar window looks identical.
    The maturity outcome does not.
  </p>

  <h3>A concrete calendar failure example</h3>

  <p>
    Consider a location with a typical frost window and heat budget like this:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>Last frost: May 25 (50% probability)</li>
    <li>First frost: September 25 (50% probability)</li>
    <li>Typical seasonal accumulation: ~1,700 GDD (base 50°F)</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    A tomato variety labeled “100 days to maturity” appears safe on the calendar.
    But if that variety requires ~1,900 GDD, it will not reach full maturity before frost in a typical year.
  </p>

  <p>
    The calendar window appears adequate.
    The heat budget does not.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Your Seasonal Heat Budget (Growing Degree Days)</h2>

  <p>
    Growing Degree Days measure accumulated heat over time.
    Most warm-season crops use a base temperature of <strong>50°F (10°C)</strong>.
  </p>

  <pre>
GDD = ((Daily High + Daily Low) ÷ 2) − 50
  </pre>

  <p>
    Each day contributes heat units when temperatures rise above the base threshold.
    Over the course of your frost-free window, those units accumulate into a measurable seasonal heat budget.
  </p>

  <p>
    You can estimate how many GDD typically accumulate before first frost using the
    <a href="/tools/growing-degree-day-planner/">Growing Degree Day Planner</a>.
  </p>

  <p>
    For a deeper explanation of how frost and heat interact, see
    <a href="/guides/how-frost-dates-and-growing-degree-days-work-together/">How Frost Dates and Growing Degree Days Work Together</a>.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Evaluating Crop Feasibility</h2>

  <p>
    Once you know your seasonal heat budget, the next step is comparing it to crop requirements.
    Short-season planning works best when crop heat demand aligns with what your climate typically supplies before frost returns.
  </p>

  <p>
    Crops generally fall into heat-demand tiers:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Low heat demand:</strong> often under ~1,200 GDD (many leafy greens and fast root crops)</li>
    <li><strong>Moderate heat demand:</strong> ~1,200–1,800 GDD (many common summer crops in shorter-season varieties)</li>
    <li><strong>High heat demand:</strong> 2,000–2,500+ GDD (many long-season warm crops)</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    In climates that accumulate only ~1,600–1,800 GDD before first frost,
    high heat demand crops operate near the boundary unless varieties are specifically bred for short seasons.
  </p>

  <p>
    This is the core shift:
    instead of asking “Does this crop fit my calendar?”
    you ask “Does this crop fit my seasonal heat budget?”
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Understanding Risk Buffer</h2>

  <p>
    Because frost dates are probability-based, some years end earlier and some later.
    Summer temperatures also vary — changing how quickly GDD accumulate.
  </p>

  <p>
    That means two gardens with the same “typical” frost window can experience different outcomes depending on where the year lands relative to the midpoint and how warm the season is.
  </p>

  <p>
    Three outcomes describe most short-season planting decisions:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Comfortable:</strong> your seasonal heat budget exceeds crop requirement by several hundred GDD.</li>
    <li><strong>Borderline:</strong> crop requirement closely matches your expected seasonal total.</li>
    <li><strong>Unlikely:</strong> your climate typically falls short before frost returns.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    In a moderate climate accumulating ~2,500 GDD, a crop requiring ~1,800 GDD has wide margin.
    In a short climate accumulating ~1,800 GDD, the same crop operates at the boundary —
    and a one-week early frost can remove 100–150 GDD of the buffer.
  </p>

  <p>
    Short-season planning is not about eliminating risk —
    it’s about choosing margin intentionally.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Adding 2–4 Weeks of Effective Season</h2>

  <p>
    In constrained climates, small adjustments can increase usable season length:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>Starting seeds indoors to align transplant timing with frost boundaries</li>
    <li>Using warm microclimates near south-facing walls</li>
    <li>Applying lightweight row covers to reduce early fall frost exposure</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    If indoor starts meaningfully shift transplant timing relative to frost risk,
    you can anchor scheduling using the
    <a href="/tools/seed-start-planner/">Seed Start Planner</a>.
  </p>

  <h3>What season extension changes — and what it does not</h3>

  <p>
    Season extension methods can protect crops from light frost events and may allow earlier planting or later harvest.
    However, protection from frost does not automatically increase total seasonal heat accumulation.
  </p>

  <p>
    Growing Degree Days are driven by air temperature intensity over time.
    Covers may buffer against brief exposure to 32°F, but they do not transform a 1,700 GDD climate into a 2,300 GDD climate.
  </p>

  <p>
    In short growing seasons, season extension improves margin at the boundary.
    It does not fundamentally increase the seasonal heat budget.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>The Short-Season Planning Model</h2>

  <p>
    Planning a garden in a short growing season follows a clear sequence:
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Frost → Season Length → Growing Degree Days → Crop Requirement → Risk Margin</strong>
  </p>

  <p>
    Planning becomes reliable when you treat frost dates as the boundary and GDD as the development budget.
  </p>

  <h3>Applied short-season planning example</h3>

  <p>
    Consider a gardener in a climate with:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>Last frost: May 30</li>
    <li>First frost: September 20</li>
    <li>Typical seasonal accumulation: ~1,650 GDD</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    The gardener wants to grow:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>Tomatoes requiring ~1,800 GDD</li>
    <li>Bush beans requiring ~1,200 GDD</li>
    <li>Winter squash requiring ~2,100 GDD</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Modeling the heat budget reveals:
    bush beans operate with comfortable margin;
    tomatoes operate at a moderate deficit unless short-season varieties are selected;
    winter squash operate in a structural heat deficit and are unlikely to mature reliably.
  </p>

  <p>
    The calendar may suggest all three crops “fit” inside the frost-free window.
    Heat modeling reveals that only one clearly aligns with climate constraints.
  </p>

  <h3>Deterministic recap</h3>

  <p>
    1) Identify your frost boundaries at 32°F (50% probability).<br>
    2) Define your frost-free window.<br>
    3) Estimate your typical seasonal heat accumulation.<br>
    4) Compare crop heat requirements.<br>
    5) Evaluate your margin relative to the frost boundary.
  </p>

  <p>
    When those pieces align, crop maturity becomes predictable in a typical year.
    When they do not, calendar-based planting advice often fails.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Summary</h2>

  <ul>
    <li>Short growing seasons are constrained by frost timing and limited heat accumulation.</li>
    <li>Frost dates use a 32°F definition and 50% probability framing.</li>
    <li>Growing Degree Days measure your seasonal heat budget.</li>
    <li>Crop viability depends on whether your heat budget exceeds crop requirements.</li>
    <li>Risk margin determines reliability near the frost boundary.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    In short climates, successful planning comes from modeling frost boundaries and heat accumulation together —
    not relying on calendar assumptions.
  </p>
</section>